WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.400
So level 1. Alright, google.com. Here's the

00:00:03.400 --> 00:00:06.160
logo. Here's the search bar. Oh, and here's

00:00:06.160 --> 00:00:08.700
the buttons. Why are you still waiting? Well,

00:00:08.780 --> 00:00:11.600
it's because you were missing this. This little

00:00:11.600 --> 00:00:13.200
line of text at the bottom. See, when

00:00:13.200 --> 00:00:15.720
Google launched, it was incredibly minimalistic compared to

00:00:15.720 --> 00:00:17.920
all the other search engines out there. But

00:00:17.920 --> 00:00:20.620
because of this, they had a problem. When

00:00:20.620 --> 00:00:22.460
they started making user tests in the early

00:00:22.460 --> 00:00:25.500
2000s with Stanford students, the students would sit

00:00:25.500 --> 00:00:27.680
there for 45 seconds staring at the page

00:00:27.680 --> 00:00:29.160
waiting for it to finish loading,

00:00:29.160 --> 00:00:31.840
even though it was fully loading. And that's

00:00:31.840 --> 00:00:33.360
because all the information. And that's because all

00:00:33.360 --> 00:00:34.920
the information was at the top. So how

00:00:34.920 --> 00:00:37.540
did they fix it? Well, with this. A

00:00:37.540 --> 00:00:40.600
copyright notice that has no legal need to

00:00:40.600 --> 00:00:42.620
be there, but it was put there only

00:00:42.620 --> 00:00:44.260
to let you know that the page has

00:00:44.260 --> 00:00:47.180
finished loading. See, this is only level 1

00:00:47.180 --> 00:00:49.520
of the 7 levels of the insane rabbit

00:00:49.520 --> 00:00:52.040
hole that is designing and building tech products.

00:00:52.240 --> 00:00:54.240
And these levels are what makes the difference

00:00:54.240 --> 00:00:56.600
between products that feel really bad, that you

00:00:56.600 --> 00:00:59.020
hate using, and products that end up generating

00:00:59.020 --> 00:01:01.080
billions of billions of dollars in revenue, and

00:01:01.080 --> 00:01:02.640
that end up changing the world. We're going

00:01:02.640 --> 00:01:04.800
to go from uncovering the smallest details to

00:01:04.800 --> 00:01:06.800
the entire product strategies of some of the

00:01:06.800 --> 00:01:08.840
biggest tech companies in the world. But even

00:01:08.840 --> 00:01:10.880
here at level 1, there's so much more

00:01:10.880 --> 00:01:13.020
that you don't see behind the tech that

00:01:13.020 --> 00:01:14.760
you use every day. Take a look at

00:01:14.760 --> 00:01:18.000
this. This is a nice rounded interface. So

00:01:18.000 --> 00:01:20.460
here for these checkboxes, we're going to match

00:01:20.460 --> 00:01:22.240
the style, we're going to make them round.

00:01:22.420 --> 00:01:24.500
But now you see that there's a problem.

00:01:24.860 --> 00:01:27.420
The app feels broken. And that's because by

00:01:27.420 --> 00:01:28.380
making these round,

00:01:28.380 --> 00:01:31.000
we made them look like something else that

00:01:31.000 --> 00:01:33.160
we're used to. Radio buttons, where you can

00:01:33.160 --> 00:01:35.520
only select one option at a time. This

00:01:35.520 --> 00:01:38.720
super small difference in how rounded these boxes

00:01:38.720 --> 00:01:41.500
are completely changed how we interpret what we

00:01:41.500 --> 00:01:42.940
see and what we think we can do

00:01:42.940 --> 00:01:44.680
in this screen. And that's because we have

00:01:44.680 --> 00:01:46.860
this knowledge in our brain that got reinforced

00:01:46.860 --> 00:01:50.380
over thousands of times using technology that this

00:01:50.380 --> 00:01:53.600
means only one option and this means that

00:01:53.600 --> 00:01:55.060
you can have many. Or take a look

00:01:55.060 --> 00:01:58.000
at this. Well, of course, this is a

00:01:58.000 --> 00:01:58.260
link

00:01:58.260 --> 00:02:01.500
to something. Duh. Well, no. Turns out it

00:02:01.500 --> 00:02:04.020
was just some blue underlined text. And the

00:02:04.020 --> 00:02:06.340
reason this fell off is that we were

00:02:06.340 --> 00:02:09.980
missing this. The mouse cursor changing from the

00:02:09.980 --> 00:02:12.140
regular arrow to the little hand that says,

00:02:12.280 --> 00:02:14.180
hey, there's an action here. This might seem

00:02:14.180 --> 00:02:16.820
like a small detail, but without this, our

00:02:16.820 --> 00:02:19.460
interfaces would be completely unusable. Like, for example,

00:02:19.620 --> 00:02:21.440
trying to drag some panel without the cursor

00:02:21.440 --> 00:02:24.240
becoming their size one. Without this small visual

00:02:24.240 --> 00:02:26.640
detail on your cursor, you simply wouldn't be

00:02:26.640 --> 00:02:28.180
able to use any desktop computer,

00:02:28.260 --> 00:02:30.340
and that's why this has been around from

00:02:30.340 --> 00:02:32.780
the beginning since 1987, when it was invented

00:02:32.780 --> 00:02:35.460
by Bill Atkinson for the Macintosh app HyperCard.

00:02:35.560 --> 00:02:37.640
And it's stuck around to this day. Oh,

00:02:37.720 --> 00:02:39.520
and all these interactions that you're seeing, I

00:02:39.520 --> 00:02:42.000
build them as full working prototypes using Magic

00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:43.980
Patterns, the sponsor of this video. More about

00:02:43.980 --> 00:02:45.560
it later. But take a look at these.

00:02:45.840 --> 00:02:48.040
These are files on your computer, but the

00:02:48.040 --> 00:02:50.900
file names are really long. Now, usually when

00:02:50.900 --> 00:02:52.900
you have a really, really long string on

00:02:52.900 --> 00:02:55.280
an app, this happens. It gets cut and

00:02:55.280 --> 00:02:57.400
these dots, which are called ellipses, appear to

00:02:57.400 --> 00:02:58.040
tell you that, hey,

00:02:58.040 --> 00:03:00.600
there's more. But now, with this, we cannot

00:03:00.600 --> 00:03:02.840
see which one is the file version, for

00:03:02.840 --> 00:03:05.360
example. Say, v1 or v2, which usually is

00:03:05.360 --> 00:03:07.180
stuff that's at the end of the file

00:03:07.180 --> 00:03:08.720
name. We cannot put the ellipses at the

00:03:08.720 --> 00:03:11.240
beginning either, because otherwise we lose the file

00:03:11.240 --> 00:03:11.920
name more together.

00:03:12.100 --> 00:03:14.120
So, for example, here in macOS, when we

00:03:14.120 --> 00:03:15.660
try to reduce the size of the window,

00:03:15.900 --> 00:03:17.920
the file names get the ellipses in the

00:03:17.920 --> 00:03:20.760
center, and letters get progressively cheaped away on

00:03:20.760 --> 00:03:22.940
each side of the ellipses centered in the

00:03:22.940 --> 00:03:24.260
word. So you can see the start of

00:03:24.260 --> 00:03:25.700
the file name and the end of the

00:03:25.700 --> 00:03:26.120
file name.

00:03:26.120 --> 00:03:28.420
So this means that someone had to manually

00:03:28.420 --> 00:03:29.920
go in and write all the code that

00:03:29.920 --> 00:03:31.660
calculates how many letters to chip away at

00:03:31.660 --> 00:03:33.420
each side of the ellipses just to make

00:03:33.420 --> 00:03:34.440
sure this happens.

00:03:34.620 --> 00:03:36.360
By the way, that someone is Scott Jensen,

00:03:36.660 --> 00:03:38.800
who built this, again, for Apple in the

00:03:38.800 --> 00:03:39.200
80s.

00:03:39.320 --> 00:03:41.400
See, designing tech is not just about making

00:03:41.400 --> 00:03:44.520
things look nice. These seemingly small visual details

00:03:44.520 --> 00:03:47.160
won't get noticed by 99% of people,

00:03:47.240 --> 00:03:48.960
but it's what makes our tech usable.

00:03:48.960 --> 00:03:51.080
But yeah, sometimes they are there just because

00:03:51.080 --> 00:03:53.500
they're fun. Like, for example, you drag the

00:03:53.500 --> 00:03:55.620
Google Street View yellow guy, and you can

00:03:55.620 --> 00:03:57.500
see that he's actually holding on to the

00:03:57.500 --> 00:03:59.860
cursor and reacting to gravity as you move

00:03:59.860 --> 00:04:00.240
him around.

00:04:00.500 --> 00:04:02.220
Why? Well, why not?

00:04:02.420 --> 00:04:04.000
And now let's start to go up a

00:04:04.000 --> 00:04:06.440
level, because that's when things start to get

00:04:06.440 --> 00:04:06.780
interesting.

00:04:07.080 --> 00:04:08.360
So say you're on a call with your

00:04:08.360 --> 00:04:10.440
bank. They're telling you there is a suspicious

00:04:10.440 --> 00:04:12.300
activity on your account, and they need to

00:04:12.300 --> 00:04:13.420
verify some information.

00:04:13.420 --> 00:04:15.360
So you open your banking app to check,

00:04:15.480 --> 00:04:18.300
and you see, this, Revolut, is not calling

00:04:18.300 --> 00:04:18.500
you.

00:04:18.680 --> 00:04:20.640
The people that built this app made it

00:04:20.640 --> 00:04:22.400
so that it's detecting when you're on a

00:04:22.400 --> 00:04:24.060
phone call and when you're opening the app

00:04:24.060 --> 00:04:24.740
at the same time.

00:04:24.900 --> 00:04:26.620
And because one of the most common scams

00:04:26.620 --> 00:04:28.360
is someone pretending to be your bank and

00:04:28.360 --> 00:04:29.900
asking you to do something in the app

00:04:29.900 --> 00:04:31.420
while they're on the phone with you,

00:04:31.600 --> 00:04:34.340
Do not read it! Do not read in

00:04:34.340 --> 00:04:34.780
the card!

00:04:34.980 --> 00:04:37.780
Revolut just tells you. Whoever's on the phone,

00:04:38.140 --> 00:04:38.940
well, it's not us.

00:04:39.080 --> 00:04:41.180
And this is what Level 2 is all

00:04:41.180 --> 00:04:43.260
about. It's not just how things look.

00:04:43.420 --> 00:04:45.700
It's the interactions and how they behave.

00:04:45.860 --> 00:04:48.200
And more importantly, it's about building behaviors that

00:04:48.200 --> 00:04:49.180
feel human.

00:04:49.420 --> 00:04:51.480
Like take Google Maps. Your phone has a

00:04:51.480 --> 00:04:53.940
touchscreen, and it's perfect for moving around this

00:04:53.940 --> 00:04:54.180
map.

00:04:54.300 --> 00:04:55.700
You can just drag your finger around.

00:04:55.880 --> 00:04:58.200
But zooming in still requires you to pinch

00:04:58.200 --> 00:05:00.080
the screen, so it requires two hands.

00:05:00.260 --> 00:05:02.460
We're usually trying to navigate around. We're on

00:05:02.460 --> 00:05:02.840
a bike.

00:05:03.040 --> 00:05:05.340
It's the worst possible time to require us

00:05:05.340 --> 00:05:06.060
to pinch stuff.

00:05:06.220 --> 00:05:08.740
So you end up doing this weird contortionism

00:05:08.740 --> 00:05:09.720
just to zoom in.

00:05:09.720 --> 00:05:11.280
But actually, in Google Maps, you can double

00:05:11.280 --> 00:05:13.820
tap and hold and drag your finger up

00:05:13.820 --> 00:05:15.660
and down to zoom in and out with

00:05:15.660 --> 00:05:16.240
one finger.

00:05:16.380 --> 00:05:18.220
You can actually do it in almost all

00:05:18.220 --> 00:05:20.240
the applications where you can pinch to zoom.

00:05:20.360 --> 00:05:21.620
The first time I learned about this, I

00:05:21.620 --> 00:05:23.220
was like, I'm sorry, what?

00:05:23.420 --> 00:05:25.280
But the problem with this is that while

00:05:25.280 --> 00:05:27.600
it definitely goes into the genius category, there

00:05:27.600 --> 00:05:29.380
is no way to know that you can

00:05:29.380 --> 00:05:30.200
actually do this.

00:05:30.200 --> 00:05:32.320
Most people don't even know, but one interaction

00:05:32.320 --> 00:05:34.800
that instead gets used billions of times every

00:05:34.800 --> 00:05:36.060
single day is this.

00:05:36.240 --> 00:05:37.740
You know, when you drag down the top

00:05:37.740 --> 00:05:38.720
of a list to refresh.

00:05:39.020 --> 00:05:42.040
This interaction is incredibly intuitive, and it removes

00:05:42.040 --> 00:05:44.080
the need for an additional refresh button.

00:05:44.280 --> 00:05:47.240
But while this looks totally innocuous, today this

00:05:47.240 --> 00:05:49.020
feature is used by the biggest social media

00:05:49.020 --> 00:05:49.920
companies on the planet,

00:05:50.060 --> 00:05:52.760
paired with infinite scrolling feeds, like Instagram, to

00:05:52.760 --> 00:05:55.040
show you something new every time you refresh.

00:05:55.040 --> 00:05:58.460
And this one simple interaction is probably responsible

00:05:58.460 --> 00:06:01.160
for billions of dollars of revenue in ads

00:06:01.160 --> 00:06:01.940
on these feeds.

00:06:02.240 --> 00:06:03.640
But now, let's go up a level once

00:06:03.640 --> 00:06:06.860
again, because in 2008, music streaming had a

00:06:06.860 --> 00:06:07.140
problem.

00:06:07.280 --> 00:06:08.440
Piracy was everywhere.

00:06:08.640 --> 00:06:10.900
People were illegally downloading songs all over the

00:06:10.900 --> 00:06:11.140
place.

00:06:11.280 --> 00:06:13.000
And if I wanted to purchase my entire

00:06:13.000 --> 00:06:16.240
current Spotify library legally on iTunes back then,

00:06:16.360 --> 00:06:18.220
it would have run me $3,800.

00:06:18.760 --> 00:06:20.060
And I would have to synchronize all these

00:06:20.060 --> 00:06:22.060
songs manually on all of my devices.

00:06:22.060 --> 00:06:23.960
And that's when Spotify came in.

00:06:24.120 --> 00:06:25.120
But they had a problem.

00:06:25.300 --> 00:06:27.820
See, they started with this promise of instant

00:06:27.820 --> 00:06:28.780
music streaming.

00:06:29.120 --> 00:06:31.260
Just choose a track and immediately listen to

00:06:31.260 --> 00:06:31.400
it.

00:06:31.540 --> 00:06:33.400
But the problem is that internet speeds back

00:06:33.400 --> 00:06:36.980
then, especially mobile, weren't anywhere near as fast

00:06:36.980 --> 00:06:37.640
as they are today.

00:06:37.860 --> 00:06:39.220
They tried what anyone would.

00:06:39.400 --> 00:06:41.280
Just host the songs on their servers, and

00:06:41.280 --> 00:06:43.640
anytime someone needs a song, just stream it

00:06:43.640 --> 00:06:44.480
down to the device.

00:06:44.780 --> 00:06:46.120
And it was atrocious.

00:06:46.720 --> 00:06:48.240
It could take from 30 seconds to a

00:06:48.240 --> 00:06:50.560
full minute for a song to start playing.

00:06:50.740 --> 00:06:51.880
So that's when they had an idea.

00:06:52.060 --> 00:06:55.000
They bought a company that actually powered piracy.

00:06:55.260 --> 00:06:57.540
And that you might remember called uTorrent.

00:06:57.720 --> 00:06:59.380
And sold uTorrent almost immediately.

00:06:59.620 --> 00:07:01.140
But the reason they did this is to

00:07:01.140 --> 00:07:03.020
get this one guy.

00:07:03.260 --> 00:07:04.420
Ludwig Strigus.

00:07:04.560 --> 00:07:06.920
And he rebuilt Spotify's infrastructure at the time

00:07:06.920 --> 00:07:09.540
using the same technology that powered piracy.

00:07:09.700 --> 00:07:10.220
Peer to peer.

00:07:10.360 --> 00:07:11.600
See, when you play the song, it came

00:07:11.600 --> 00:07:12.880
from three places at once.

00:07:13.040 --> 00:07:15.700
Spotify servers, your own cash, and other Spotify

00:07:15.700 --> 00:07:16.600
users near you.

00:07:16.600 --> 00:07:19.160
A 2010 study found that only 8.8

00:07:19.160 --> 00:07:21.520
% of the music came from Spotify servers.

00:07:21.640 --> 00:07:24.040
36% came from other users, and the

00:07:24.040 --> 00:07:26.620
rest was smartly downloaded already on your device.

00:07:26.820 --> 00:07:28.880
They took the exact technology that the music

00:07:28.880 --> 00:07:31.420
industry were suing people over, and used it

00:07:31.420 --> 00:07:32.940
to build a legal alternative.

00:07:33.240 --> 00:07:35.940
And as a user, you never noticed.

00:07:36.180 --> 00:07:38.540
You just clicked on a song, and it

00:07:38.540 --> 00:07:38.780
worked.

00:07:38.780 --> 00:07:40.460
See, most people think that great products are

00:07:40.460 --> 00:07:42.120
built around great technology.

00:07:42.320 --> 00:07:44.480
But most of the times, it's the opposite

00:07:44.480 --> 00:07:45.180
that happens.

00:07:45.380 --> 00:07:46.740
You have a great idea for how the

00:07:46.740 --> 00:07:49.220
perfect interaction and experience looks like, and then

00:07:49.220 --> 00:07:51.480
you find the technology that makes it possible.

00:07:51.680 --> 00:07:53.780
Because the ones that really matter are those

00:07:53.780 --> 00:07:56.040
that make incredible experiences possible.

00:07:56.220 --> 00:07:59.240
But also where the technology disappears, and you

00:07:59.240 --> 00:08:00.340
never see it.

