00:11:15.100 --> 00:11:16.480
But now, let's go back to the video,

00:11:16.640 --> 00:11:18.480
because now that we get to level 5,

00:11:18.700 --> 00:11:21.000
we start to blur the boundaries between product

00:11:21.000 --> 00:11:22.320
design and product strategy.

00:11:22.320 --> 00:11:23.760
And this is where you start to see

00:11:23.760 --> 00:11:26.560
the more important product decisions that shape how

00:11:26.560 --> 00:11:27.560
we use something.

00:11:27.780 --> 00:11:29.340
So, let me show you how I personally

00:11:29.340 --> 00:11:32.000
used level 5 to build this.

00:11:32.300 --> 00:11:33.400
This is Flask.

00:11:33.540 --> 00:11:35.740
It's my own company and my own product.

00:11:35.920 --> 00:11:37.440
It's a video collaboration tool where you can

00:11:37.440 --> 00:11:38.320
collaborate on videos,

00:11:38.480 --> 00:11:40.000
record comments, and share your screen.

00:11:40.120 --> 00:11:41.740
And all of the comments appear visually right

00:11:41.740 --> 00:11:42.540
on the video's timeline.

00:11:42.780 --> 00:11:44.240
Now, for every comment, we need to give

00:11:44.240 --> 00:11:46.640
out key information that we cannot miss.

00:11:46.780 --> 00:11:49.060
For example, who created the comment, Enrico in

00:11:49.060 --> 00:11:49.400
this case,

00:11:49.400 --> 00:11:51.760
when this was added, or which timestamp it's

00:11:51.760 --> 00:11:52.740
referencing in the video.

00:11:52.840 --> 00:11:54.180
You also need a way to mark the

00:11:54.180 --> 00:11:54.900
comment as done.

00:11:55.220 --> 00:11:57.620
Now, the most basic approach that any designer

00:11:57.620 --> 00:11:59.120
would take is this.

00:11:59.460 --> 00:12:00.900
Find a nice way to get them out,

00:12:01.000 --> 00:12:01.860
and you're done.

00:12:02.060 --> 00:12:04.100
For example, this is what my main competitor

00:12:04.100 --> 00:12:04.480
does.

00:12:04.640 --> 00:12:06.000
You have all the info right here, and

00:12:06.000 --> 00:12:07.460
you can mark a comment as done right

00:12:07.460 --> 00:12:07.720
there.

00:12:07.840 --> 00:12:09.540
But instead, what if we take a level

00:12:09.540 --> 00:12:11.480
5 strategic approach to this,

00:12:11.620 --> 00:12:13.380
where we don't just think about how to

00:12:13.380 --> 00:12:14.560
arrange things visually,

00:12:14.560 --> 00:12:16.940
but how to architect the logic of the

00:12:16.940 --> 00:12:19.440
entire app to make this all much more

00:12:19.440 --> 00:12:19.940
elegant.

00:12:20.080 --> 00:12:22.240
For example, instead of deciding that this is

00:12:22.240 --> 00:12:23.180
a done toggle,

00:12:23.340 --> 00:12:25.380
why don't we create the general purpose tagging

00:12:25.380 --> 00:12:25.720
system,

00:12:25.960 --> 00:12:28.060
where each element can have custom tags.

00:12:28.320 --> 00:12:30.300
And then we'll create a default one called

00:12:30.300 --> 00:12:30.760
done,

00:12:30.900 --> 00:12:32.020
and another one called important.

00:12:32.180 --> 00:12:33.540
So we can show users that you can

00:12:33.540 --> 00:12:35.300
actually have more than one at a time.

00:12:35.400 --> 00:12:37.080
And now, these are not fixed in place.

00:12:37.240 --> 00:12:38.680
If you don't like done, and you want

00:12:38.680 --> 00:12:39.600
to use it for something else,

00:12:39.740 --> 00:12:40.920
you can just delete it.

00:12:41.000 --> 00:12:42.720
But as people started to request more and

00:12:42.720 --> 00:12:43.320
more features,

00:12:43.320 --> 00:12:45.100
they wanted to be able to filter by

00:12:45.100 --> 00:12:45.460
user,

00:12:45.780 --> 00:12:47.860
or by custom tag, or by creation date,

00:12:47.960 --> 00:12:49.820
and it was getting so complicated.

00:12:50.020 --> 00:12:52.260
So instead, we're going to make one structural

00:12:52.260 --> 00:12:53.320
design change,

00:12:53.440 --> 00:12:55.640
and say that everything is a tag.

00:12:55.760 --> 00:12:57.660
So now the creator becomes a tag.

00:12:57.800 --> 00:12:59.280
The creation time becomes a tag.

00:12:59.440 --> 00:13:01.740
Even the link timestamp becomes a tag.

00:13:01.900 --> 00:13:03.980
Now, these are not editable by the user,

00:13:04.120 --> 00:13:05.360
but watch what happens.

00:13:05.580 --> 00:13:07.140
Now I can create a filtering system

00:13:07.140 --> 00:13:09.620
that filters by multiple types of tags in

00:13:09.620 --> 00:13:10.320
the same place,

00:13:10.360 --> 00:13:12.240
and it all feels logical.

00:13:12.240 --> 00:13:13.920
Now I don't need to have a dedicated

00:13:13.920 --> 00:13:15.680
row up top with its own layout.

00:13:15.860 --> 00:13:17.740
I can just have a list of tags.

00:13:18.020 --> 00:13:19.080
And now, a while later,

00:13:19.240 --> 00:13:20.540
I had to build a system to notify

00:13:20.540 --> 00:13:22.740
users of new comments that got added

00:13:22.740 --> 00:13:24.120
since they last visited.

00:13:24.300 --> 00:13:26.020
Normally, I would have to create an entirely

00:13:26.020 --> 00:13:26.600
new view

00:13:26.600 --> 00:13:27.880
to show these comments.

00:13:28.060 --> 00:13:30.240
But now that we made this structural design

00:13:30.240 --> 00:13:30.680
decision

00:13:30.680 --> 00:13:32.420
that everything is a tag,

00:13:32.580 --> 00:13:33.680
you can see that I just need to

00:13:33.680 --> 00:13:36.000
add a tag called new to the comments.

00:13:36.180 --> 00:13:38.280
And clicking here will just trigger a filter

00:13:38.280 --> 00:13:39.420
for that tag,

00:13:39.420 --> 00:13:41.760
which uses all the existing stuff that we

00:13:41.760 --> 00:13:42.620
already built before.

00:13:42.780 --> 00:13:44.900
Having a great structural design in the logic

00:13:44.900 --> 00:13:46.000
of how your app works

00:13:46.000 --> 00:13:48.440
makes everything else simpler.

00:13:48.620 --> 00:13:50.180
That's why in a similar way to Flask,

00:13:50.320 --> 00:13:52.560
Notion took the decision to make everything a

00:13:52.560 --> 00:13:52.820
page.

00:13:53.020 --> 00:13:54.700
Even though it might be displayed as a

00:13:54.700 --> 00:13:56.080
calendar or a feed or a table,

00:13:56.480 --> 00:13:57.260
everything is a page.

00:13:57.460 --> 00:13:59.600
Or while Slack decided that everything is a

00:13:59.600 --> 00:13:59.880
channel.

00:13:59.880 --> 00:14:02.440
These are all examples of level 5.

00:14:02.720 --> 00:14:04.660
But at level 6 is where we start

00:14:04.660 --> 00:14:05.860
to leave product design

00:14:05.860 --> 00:14:07.540
as you think about it and start to

00:14:07.540 --> 00:14:09.660
enter the realm of product strategy.

00:14:09.920 --> 00:14:12.000
See, for example, video has been around forever.

00:14:12.220 --> 00:14:13.600
You can record yourself on your phone.

00:14:13.720 --> 00:14:14.880
You can have a video call on Zoom.

00:14:15.020 --> 00:14:15.860
You can upload to YouTube.

00:14:16.060 --> 00:14:17.060
Video is soft.

00:14:17.180 --> 00:14:18.660
We don't need any more video products.

00:14:18.820 --> 00:14:21.120
But then Loom came along and said,

00:14:21.200 --> 00:14:23.980
what if video wasn't for entertainment or for

00:14:23.980 --> 00:14:24.560
live calls,

00:14:24.660 --> 00:14:26.480
but for replacing meetings?

00:14:26.680 --> 00:14:28.340
What if instead of scheduling 30 minutes with

00:14:28.340 --> 00:14:28.740
your team,

00:14:28.740 --> 00:14:30.980
you just record a 3-minute video and

00:14:30.980 --> 00:14:31.540
send it out?

00:14:31.700 --> 00:14:33.380
They didn't invent video.

00:14:33.560 --> 00:14:34.540
They didn't invent recording.

00:14:34.680 --> 00:14:35.680
They didn't invent players.

00:14:35.840 --> 00:14:37.980
They reframed what video is for.

00:14:38.300 --> 00:14:40.620
And this little reframe built a company that

00:14:40.620 --> 00:14:43.600
Atlassian bought for $975 million.

00:14:44.240 --> 00:14:45.660
Or take Superhuman.

00:14:45.880 --> 00:14:47.440
Email has been around for decades.

00:14:47.720 --> 00:14:48.500
Gmail is free.

00:14:48.940 --> 00:14:50.760
What could you possibly do here?

00:14:51.100 --> 00:14:54.300
Well, Superhuman reframed email from inbox you need

00:14:54.300 --> 00:14:54.760
to manage

00:14:54.760 --> 00:14:57.780
to the fastest email out there.

00:14:57.780 --> 00:14:59.820
They added keyboard shortcuts for everything.

00:14:59.940 --> 00:15:01.540
They show you how long it takes to

00:15:01.540 --> 00:15:02.760
get through your inbox.

00:15:03.000 --> 00:15:05.160
They gamified going to inbox zero.

00:15:05.340 --> 00:15:07.680
And that's how they charge $30 a month

00:15:07.680 --> 00:15:08.100
for it.

00:15:08.340 --> 00:15:09.840
This is what level 6 is all about.

00:15:10.020 --> 00:15:11.220
The technology doesn't change.

00:15:11.380 --> 00:15:12.320
The framing doesn't change.

00:15:12.480 --> 00:15:13.860
Hell, the design might not even change.

00:15:13.980 --> 00:15:15.600
But the right strategic decision here

00:15:15.600 --> 00:15:18.160
can create billions of dollars worth of company.

00:15:18.320 --> 00:15:20.560
And now we finally get to level 7.

00:15:20.860 --> 00:15:23.260
This is Steve Jobs kind of territory.

00:15:23.260 --> 00:15:26.180
Get rid of all these buttons and just

00:15:26.180 --> 00:15:27.260
make a giant screen.

00:15:27.500 --> 00:15:29.560
See, at the time, this sounded insane.

00:15:29.780 --> 00:15:30.640
Blackberry was king.

00:15:30.820 --> 00:15:32.160
Physical keyboards were essential.

00:15:32.360 --> 00:15:34.360
The idea that you could type accurately on

00:15:34.360 --> 00:15:34.740
a touchscreen

00:15:34.740 --> 00:15:36.220
was considered fantasy.

00:15:36.420 --> 00:15:37.260
And here's the thing.

00:15:37.360 --> 00:15:38.840
It wasn't even a new idea.

00:15:39.020 --> 00:15:41.200
In 1984, a company called General Magic

00:15:41.200 --> 00:15:43.380
spun off from Apple and shipped the Sonic

00:15:43.380 --> 00:15:44.000
Magic Link,

00:15:44.240 --> 00:15:45.680
a handheld device with a touchscreen

00:15:45.680 --> 00:15:47.780
where you could do email, calendar, notes,

00:15:47.780 --> 00:15:51.160
the first smartphone 13 years before the iPhone.

00:15:51.320 --> 00:15:52.420
And it flopped.

00:15:52.520 --> 00:15:53.980
So what is the difference here?

00:15:54.200 --> 00:15:55.600
It's the same vision, the same bed,

00:15:55.900 --> 00:15:57.320
but a completely different outcome.

00:15:57.520 --> 00:15:59.540
The difference was everything underneath.

00:15:59.880 --> 00:16:02.020
General Magic, just like Steve Jobs a few

00:16:02.020 --> 00:16:02.560
years later,

00:16:02.760 --> 00:16:03.820
had level 7.

00:16:03.960 --> 00:16:05.760
It's a crazy product vision.

00:16:05.960 --> 00:16:07.540
Something that completely changes things.

00:16:07.680 --> 00:16:10.060
But they didn't have all the layers underneath.

00:16:10.360 --> 00:16:11.920
And the difference between Steve Jobs and the

00:16:11.920 --> 00:16:12.420
iPhone team

00:16:12.420 --> 00:16:15.240
and everyone else is all the levels underneath.

00:16:15.240 --> 00:16:17.560
It's going to level 6 and reframing the

00:16:17.560 --> 00:16:17.800
phone

00:16:17.800 --> 00:16:19.180
from a device that makes calls

00:16:19.180 --> 00:16:20.700
to a computer in your pocket.

00:16:20.880 --> 00:16:23.020
Not a phone with apps, but apps with

00:16:23.020 --> 00:16:23.340
a phone.

00:16:23.700 --> 00:16:25.120
It's going back to level 5.

00:16:25.240 --> 00:16:27.360
The structural decision that everything is an app,

00:16:27.540 --> 00:16:30.380
no file system, no complex desktop-like UI,

00:16:30.580 --> 00:16:33.860
everything is in this neat grid of apps.

00:16:34.020 --> 00:16:36.080
It's going back to level 4, the defaults.

00:16:36.200 --> 00:16:38.220
The App Store ships with Apple's apps front

00:16:38.220 --> 00:16:38.660
and center.

00:16:38.820 --> 00:16:39.860
Safari defaults to Google.

00:16:40.080 --> 00:16:41.960
The home button always takes you home.

00:16:42.140 --> 00:16:44.080
And of course, you need level 3,

00:16:44.080 --> 00:16:45.100
the technical innovation.

00:16:45.380 --> 00:16:47.440
Capacitive multi-touch that actually works.

00:16:47.580 --> 00:16:48.900
Gorilla Glass that doesn't break.

00:16:49.060 --> 00:16:50.260
A battery that lasts a day.

00:16:50.420 --> 00:16:51.460
And going back to level 2,

00:16:51.620 --> 00:16:53.620
the interactions, inventing pinch to zoom,

00:16:54.000 --> 00:16:54.660
slide to unlock,

00:16:54.840 --> 00:16:56.940
the rubber band bouncy feel when you scroll

00:16:56.940 --> 00:16:57.440
too far.

00:16:57.660 --> 00:16:59.020
And all the way to level 1,

00:16:59.180 --> 00:17:01.160
the details, the squircles on every icon,

00:17:01.300 --> 00:17:02.180
the weight of the animation.

00:17:02.620 --> 00:17:04.720
And Ken Cosienta, an engineer with a deadline,

00:17:04.900 --> 00:17:06.620
fingered out that you need to make

00:17:06.620 --> 00:17:08.480
the invisible hitboxes of the keyboard

00:17:08.480 --> 00:17:10.700
dynamically bigger based on the letter you were

00:17:10.700 --> 00:17:11.020
typing.

00:17:11.020 --> 00:17:13.160
Otherwise, your keyboard wouldn't work.

00:17:13.280 --> 00:17:15.080
But what you saw is just the beginning.

